## Microservices with Unreal

### How it works

1. Define `[ClientCallable]` endpoints in C# microservices
2. Run `beam project build` to generate OpenAPI specs
3. Run `beam project generate-client` to auto-generate Unreal C++ and Blueprint client code
4. Call the generated subsystem from Unreal

Client code is 100% auto-generated. Never write microservice client code manually.

### Workflow

```bash
# 1. Create the microservice
beam project new service MyService -q

# 2. Implement [ClientCallable] endpoints in C#

# 3. Build — generates OpenAPI spec
beam project build --ids MyService -q

# 4. Generate Unreal client code
beam project generate-client -q
```

### Generated code structure

After generation, a plugin is created with this layout:

```
Plugins/BeamableUnrealMicroserviceClients/
  Source/.../Public/AutoGen/
    SubSystems/
      BeamMyServiceApi.h              ← API subsystem (entry point)
      MyService/
        MyServiceDoSomethingRequest.h ← Request object per endpoint
    MyServiceDoSomethingResponse.h    ← Response type
    DoSomethingRequestArgs.h          ← Request parameter struct
```

### Calling from C++

```cpp
// 1. Get the auto-generated engine subsystem
auto* Api = GEngine->GetEngineSubsystem<UBeamMyServiceApi>();

// 2. Create the request
auto* Request = UMyServiceDoSomethingRequest::Make(
    PlayerId, GetOwner(), TMap<FString, FString>{});

// 3. Call with lambda handler
FBeamRequestContext OutContext;
Api->CPP_DoSomething(
    Request,
    FOnMyServiceDoSomethingFullResponse::CreateLambda(
        [](const auto& Response) {
            if (Response.bSuccess)
            {
                // Use Response.SuccessData->...
            }
        }),
    OutContext);
```

### Calling from Blueprints

The same endpoints are exposed as Blueprint nodes:
- Search for the service name in the Blueprint action menu
- Nodes have **Success**, **Error**, and **Complete** delegate pins
- Request parameters are exposed as input pins on the request `Make` node

### Which attributes generate Unreal client code

| Attribute | Generates Unreal client code | Who can call |
|-----------|------------------------------|-------------|
| `[Callable]` | Yes | Anyone (no auth) |
| `[ClientCallable]` | Yes | Any Beamable user or developer |
| `[AdminOnlyCallable]` | Yes | Beamable admin accounts |
| `[ServerCallable]` | **No** | Portal extensions, other microservices |

> **Note:** Unity client generation differs — `[AdminOnlyCallable]` is skipped for Unity but generated for Unreal. `[ServerCallable]` is skipped for both. Use `CallableFlags.SkipGenerateClientFiles` to opt out of generation for any attribute on both platforms.

### Federation (external auth)

Microservices implementing `IFederatedLogin<T>` auto-generate:
- Getter functions for the federation identity (e.g., `GetSteamId()`)
- Blueprint-accessible data nodes

To authenticate from Unreal using a federated identity:
```cpp
auto* Runtime = GetGameInstance()->GetSubsystem<UBeamRuntime>();
Runtime->CPP_LoginFederatedOperation(
    FUserSlot("Player0"),
    "MyService",          // microservice name
    "steam",              // federation ID
    ExternalToken,        // token from external provider
    FBeamOperationEventHandlerCode::CreateLambda([](FBeamOperationEvent Evt) {
        // Player is now authenticated
    }));
```

